painting-styles.name: Realism
painting-styles.description: Focuses on depicting subjects as they appear in everyday life, without embellishment or interpretation.

painting-styles.name: Impressionism
painting-styles.description: Captures the impression of a moment, especially in terms of light and color. Often characterized by visible brush strokes.

painting-styles.name: Cubism
painting-styles.description: Breaks objects into geometric shapes and presents multiple perspectives simultaneously. Often abstract.

painting-styles.name: Post-Impressionism
painting-styles.description: Builds on Impressionism but emphasizes more on geometric forms, distortion for expressive effect, and the use of unnatural or arbitrary color.

painting-styles.name: Expressionism
painting-styles.description: Focuses on representing emotional experiences rather than physical reality. Often uses bold colors and exaggerated forms.

painting-styles.name: Surrealism
painting-styles.description: Features dream-like scenes and illogical, fantastical images. Emphasizes the subconscious mind.

painting-styles.name: Abstract Expressionism
painting-styles.description: Focuses on expressing emotions through abstract forms, often with a sense of spontaneity and personal expression.

painting-styles.name: Pop Art
painting-styles.description: Incorporates imagery from popular and mass culture, such as advertising, comic books, and everyday objects. Often uses bright colors and bold graphics.

painting-styles.name: Fauvism
painting-styles.description: Characterized by bold, often distorted forms and vibrant colors. Focuses on painterly qualities and strong color over representational or realistic values.

painting-styles.name: Art Nouveau
painting-styles.description: Emphasizes ornamental style with flowing, sinuous lines and often incorporates floral and other natural forms.

painting-styles.name: Baroque
painting-styles.description: Known for its grandeur, drama, movement, and tension. Often features intense contrasts of light and dark.

painting-styles.name: Rococo
painting-styles.description: Light, ornate, and decorative style that often depicts themes of love, nature, and playful subjects.

painting-styles.name: Neoclassicism
painting-styles.description: Draws inspiration from the "classical" art and culture of Ancient Greece and Rome. Emphasizes simplicity and symmetry.

painting-styles.name: Romanticism
painting-styles.description: Emphasizes emotion, individualism, and the glorification of the past and nature. Often dramatic and intense.

painting-styles.name: Symbolism
painting-styles.description: Uses symbolic images and indirect suggestion to express mystical ideas, emotions, and states of mind.

painting-styles.name: Photorealism
painting-styles.description: Focuses on creating paintings that are extremely realistic, often resembling high-resolution photographs.

painting-styles.name: Minimalism
painting-styles.description: Characterized by simplicity and the use of a minimal number of elements. Focuses on the essentials.

painting-styles.name: Op Art
painting-styles.description: Uses optical illusions to create a sense of movement or warping in the viewer's perception.

painting-styles.name: Art Deco
painting-styles.description: Combines modernist styles with fine craftsmanship and rich materials. Often characterized by bold geometric shapes.

painting-styles.name: Dadaism
painting-styles.description: An avant-garde movement that emphasizes absurdity and the irrational. Often uses found objects and nonsense.

painting-styles.name: Constructivism
painting-styles.description: An artistic and architectural philosophy that originated in Russia, characterized by abstract and austere compositions.

painting-styles.name: Futurism
painting-styles.description: Emphasizes speed, technology, and modernity. Often features dynamic movement and the energy of the modern world.

painting-styles.name: Neo-Expressionism
painting-styles.description: Revives the expressiveness of early 20th-century Expressionism, often with a raw, emotional quality.

painting-styles.name: Luminism
painting-styles.description: An American landscape painting style characterized by effects of light in landscapes, through the use of aerial perspective and the concealment of visible brushstrokes.

painting-styles.name: Primitivism
painting-styles.description: Borrowing visual forms from non-Western or prehistoric peoples, often characterized by a simple, unsophisticated style.
